body:
If we can settle on a design, it looks like I'll have time to contribute the implementation.

I think the public interface is just:

```cs
public interface IUserData {
    T Get<T>();
    void Set<T>(T instance);
}
```

The setter allows resetting the instance if there's a type that someone wants to use the doesn't have a `Reset()` member (e.g., immutable types).

Not sure if `T` needs a `class` constraint. I'm thinking no, so you can put a `Guid` or similar in the user data without explicitly wrapping in a box.

@chwarr if the public interface is the one mentioned in your comment, does it make sense to let it be a getter and a setter of the type `IServiceProvider` instead? I.e. something along the lines of:

```csharp
public class ServerCallContext
{
    IServiceProvider ServiceProvider { get; set; }
}
```

There already exists a good implementation for `IServiceProvider` and I do not see a reason that justifies reinventing that wheel.

> does it make sense to let it be a getter and a setter of the type `IServiceProvider` instead? I.e. something along the lines of:
> 
> ```cs
> public class ServerCallContext
> {
>     IServiceProvider ServiceProvider { get; set; }
> }
> ```

@dpsenner, I tried to come up with a way to make just a mutable `IServiceProvider` work, but I can't. The fundamental problem is that `IServiceProvider` doesn't provide any way to add new types to the UserData.

I see the need to be able to compose multiple sets of collaborating interceptors. For example, a service consumes an authN + authZ set developed by team A, an instrumentation set developed by team B, and a cross-cutting business logic set developed by team C. Each of these sets consists of multiple interceptors, depending on which functionality the service wants to opt-in to.

These sets of interceptors don't collaborate with each other to store their per-call data in the same type, but they also don't conflict with each other. (The interceptors within a set do collaborate with each other.)

A single, settable `IServiceProvider` doesn't work in this case. It either forces them to conflict with each other or it forces them to collaborate with each other.

The forced conflict arises when the independent sets perform their per-call initialization. Since each set needs some type to store its per-call data, the first interceptors in each set does something like this:

```cs
var sp = new ConcreateServiceProvider.Add<SomeType>().Build();
serverCallContext.ServiceProvider = sp;
```

Now, whichever initialization interceptor runs last wins, destroying the work the others have done.

The forced collaboration arises when trying to solve this. Some sort of initialization interceptor gets added that now knows about all the types across all the sets. ASP.NET Core takes this approach by fully embracing `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`. I assume that gRPC C# doesn't want to have an opinion about whether or how to use that library.

These problems can be addressed with some changes to the interface, but not without trade-offs.

```cs
interface IUserData // attempt 1
{
    IServiceProvider ServiceProvider { get; }
    void AddService<T>(T instance);
}
```

In attempt 1, the members exposed are mismatched: there's one to retrieve the collection and one to add an item to it. However, to get an item, a chain of calls is needed: `ServiceProvider.GetService<T>()`.

```cs
interface IUserData : IServiceProvider // attempt 2
{
    void AddService(Type forType, object instance);
}
```

Attempt 2 is better. The members are now `GetService(...)` and `AddService(...)`. This does allows use of *some* `IServiceProvider` extension methods, like `GetRequiredService()`, but not ones like `CreateScope()`.

However, this approach doesn't provide anything from `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`, like lifetimes or scopes; I suspect it would confound expectations.

```cs
public interface IUserData // original proposal, slightly amended
{
    T Get<T>();
    void Set<T>(T instance);
    // perhaps also
    void Set<TType, TImplementation>(TImplementation instance);
}
```

This interface is just paired getter(s) and setters. It's job is to be a per-call state bag. It doesn't depend on the package or the ideas from `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`, but it doesn't get in their way. It can be composed with an existing implementation of `IServiceProvider` with some ceremony, but not too much:

```cs
public StartScopeInterceptor
{
    private readonly IServiceProvider sp;

    public override Task<TResponse> UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>(TRequest request, ServerCallContext context, UnaryServerMethod<TRequest, TResponse> continuation)
    {
        context.UserData.Set(sp);
        // or, perhaps, if the ServiceProvider is known to support scopes
        context.UserData.Set(sp.CreateScope().ServiceProvider);
        return continuation(request, context);
    }
}
```

If anyone is aware of an existing interface with similar semantics elsewhere, let me know. Bonus points for an implementation.
